  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Prove or disprove the following conjectures.\prelistskip
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                There is an even integer which can be expressed as the sum of three even integers.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Every even integer can be expressed as the sum of three even integers.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                There is an odd integer which can be expressed as the sum of two odd integers.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Every odd integer can be expressed as the sum of three odd integers.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li class="custom-list-style-type">
              <p>
                <em>To get a feel about whether a claim is true or false,
                try out some examples.
                If you believe a claim is false,
                provide a specific counterexample.
                If you believe a claim is true, give a formal proof.</em>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>P</m> be the proposition:
          <sq>Every positive integer is divisible by thirteen.</sq>\prelistskip
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write <m>P</m> using quantifiers.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What is the negation of <m>P</m>?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is <m>P</m> true or false?
                Prove your assertion.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove or disprove: There exist integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> such that <m>2m-3n=15</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove or disprove: There exist integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> such that <m>6m-3n=11</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Prove or disprove: There exist a line <m>L</m> in <m>\R^2</m> such that,
          for all points <m>A, B \in \R^2</m>,
          we have <m>A, B</m> lie on <m>L</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="ex_rationalsdenseinthemselves">
        <p>
          Prove that between any two distinct rational numbers there exists another rational number.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Consider the statement: For any non-zero rational number <m>r</m> and any irrational number <m>t</m>,
          <m>rt</m> is irrational.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Translate this statement into logic using quantifiers and propositional functions.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove the statement.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>p</m> be an odd integer.
          Prove that <m>x^2-x-p=0</m> has no
          <em>integer</em> solutions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Prove: For every positive integer <m>n</m>,
          <m>n^2+n+3</m> is an odd integer greater than or equal to 5.
          <em>There are two claims here:
          <m>n^2+n+3</m> is odd, and <m>n^2+n+3\ge 5</m>.</em>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          In this question,
          you should use the following definition of the rational numbers.
          <definition>
            <statement>
              <p>
                A real number <m>x</m> is <em>rational</em>
                if it may be written in the form
                <m>x=\frac pq</m> where <m>p</m> is an integer and <m>q</m> is a positive integer.
                <m>x</m> is <em>irrational</em> if it is not rational.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
          Prove or disprove the following conjectures.
          <conjecture>
            <title>1</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are real numbers such that <m>3x+5y</m> is irrational,
                then at least one of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> is irrational.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </conjecture>
          <conjecture>
            <title>2</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are rational numbers,
                then <m>3x+4xy+2y</m> is rational.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </conjecture>
          <conjecture>
            <title>3</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are irrational numbers,
                then <m>3x+4xy+2y</m> is irrational.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </conjecture>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <em>(Snake-like integers)</em> Let's say that an integer <m>y</m> is <em>Snake-like</em>
          if and only if there is some integer <m>k</m> such that <m>y=(6k)^2+9</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Give three examples and three non-examples of Snake-like integers.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Given <m>y\in\Z</m>, compute the negation of the statement,
                <sq><m>y</m> is Snake-like.</sq>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that every Snake-like integer is a multiple of <m>9</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that the statements, <sq><m>n</m> is Snake-like,</sq> and,
                <sq><m>n</m> is a multiple of nine,</sq> are not equivalent.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Prove that it is never the case that
          <m>x^2 = 2y^2</m> for integers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Here is an alternative argument that <m>\sqrt 2</m> is irrational.
          Suppose that <m>\sqrt 2=\frac mn</m> where <m>m,n\in\N</m>.
          This time we don't assume that <m>m,n</m> have no common factors.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>m,n</m> satisfy the equation <m>m^2=2n^2</m>.
                Prove that there exist positive integers <m>m_1,n_1</m> which satisfy the following three conditions:
                <me>
                  m_1^2=2n_1^2,\qquad\qquad m_1\lt m,\qquad\qquad n_1\lt n
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that there exist two sequences of decreasing positive integers
                <m>m>m_1>m_2>\cdots</m> and <m>n>n_1>n_2>\cdots</m> which satisfy
                <m>m_i^2=2n_i^2</m> for all <m>i\in\N</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is it possible to have an infinite sequence of decreasing
                <em>positive</em> integers?
                Why not?
                Show that we obtain a contradiction and thus conclude that <m>\sqrt 2\not\in\Q</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        This is an example of the <em>method of infinite descent,</em>
        which is very important in number theory.
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The real numbers have the <em>Archimedean property</em>,
          that is, for any positive real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
          there exists a positive integer <m>n</m> such that <m>nx > y</m>.
          Use this fact to show that there do not exist any positive real numbers which are less than <m>1/n</m> for all positive integers <m>n</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Consider the following proof of the fact that every real number is less than some positive integer:
          <proof>
            <p>
              Consider a real number <m>x</m>.
              For example, <m>x = 19.7</m>.
              Then <m>x \lt 20</m> and <m>20</m> is a positive integer.
            </p>
          </proof>
          What is wrong with this proof?
          Give a correct proof.
          <hint>
            <p>
              use the previous exercise.
            </p>
          </hint>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Here is an extension of <xref ref="ex_rationalsdenseinthemselves">question</xref>.
          Let <m>\lceil x\rceil</m>, the <em>ceiling</em> of <m>x</m>,
          denote the smallest integer greater than or equal to <m>x</m>.
          E.g.<nbsp/><m>\lceil 3.2\rceil=4</m>,
          <m>\lceil 7\rceil=7</m> and <m>\lceil -8.4\rceil=-8</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Suppose that <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are real numbers with <m>x\lt y</m>.
                Use the ceiling function to show that there exists a positive integer <m>n</m> for which <m>n(y-x)>1</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove or disprove: <m>\forall x,y\in\R</m> with <m>x\lt y</m>,
                <m>\exists m,n\in\Z</m> for which <m>nx\lt m\lt ny</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use parts (a) and (b) to prove that between any two real numbers there exists a rational number.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                (Hard) Is it true that between any two real numbers there exists an
                <em>irrational</em> number?
                If so, prove it.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Suppose that <m>x,y,z</m> are real numbers such that <m>x + y + z = 1</m>.
          Prove
          <me>
            (1 - x)(1 - y)(1 - z) \geq 8 xyz
          </me>.
          <hint>
            <p>
              find a way to apply the AM-GM inequality.
            </p>
          </hint>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          You are given the following facts.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                All polynomials are continuous.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                (Intermediate Value Theorem) If <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>[a,b]</m> and <m>L</m> lies between <m>f(a)</m> and <m>f(b)</m>,
                then <m>f(x)=L</m> for some <m>x\in(a,b)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>f'(x)>0</m> on an interval,
                then <m>f</m> is an increasing function.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        Use these facts to give a formal proof that <m>x^{17}+12x^3+13x+3=0</m> has
        <em>exactly one solution</em> <m>x</m>,
        and that <m>x</m> lies in the interval <m>(-1,0)</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          (Hard) This question uses <xref ref="defn_cont">Definition</xref>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove, directly from the definition,
                that <m>f(x)=x^2</m> is continuous at <m>x=0</m>.
                <em>If you are given <m>\epsilon>0</m>,
                what should <m>\delta</m> be?</em>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>g(x)=\begin{cases}1+x\amp \text{ if } x\ge 0,\\ x\amp \text{ if } x\lt 0, \end{cases}</m><nbsp/><nbsp/> is discontinuous at <m>x=0</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                (Very hard) Let <m>h(x)=\begin{cases}x\amp \text{ if \(x\) is rational, } \\ 0\amp \text{ if \(x\) is irrational. } \end{cases}</m><nbsp/><nbsp/> Prove that <m>f</m> is continuous
                <em>only</em> at <m>x=0</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          (Hard) In this question we prove Rolle's Theorem from calculus:
          <blockquote>
            Suppose <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>, differentiable on <m>(a,b)</m>, and <m>f(a)=f(b)=0</m>, then <m>\exists c\in(a,b)</m> such that <m>f'(c)=0</m>.
          </blockquote>
          As you work through the question,
          think about where the hypotheses are used and why we need them.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Recall the Extreme Value Theorem.
                The function <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>,
                so <m>f</m> is bounded and attains its bounds.
                Otherwise said,
                <me>
                  \exists m,M\in[a,b]\text{ such that }  \forall x\in[a,b]\text{ we have } f(m)\le f(x)\le f(M)
                </me>.
                Suppose that <m>f(m)=f(M)</m>.
                Why is the conclusion of Rolle's Theorem obvious in this case?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Now suppose that <m>f(m)\neq f(M)</m>.
                Argue that <em>at least one</em>
                of the following cases holds:
                <me>
                  f(M)>0\text{ or }  f(m)\lt 0
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Without loss of generality, we may assume that <m>f(M)>0</m>.
                By considering the function <m>-f</m>, explain why.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Assume <m>f(M)>0</m>.
                Then <m>M\neq a</m> and <m>M\neq b</m>.
                Consider the difference quotient,
                <me>
                  \frac{f(M+h)-f(M)}h
                </me>.
                Show that if <m>0\lt \nm h\lt \min\{M-a,b-M\}</m> then the difference quotient is well-defined
                (exists and makes sense).
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Suppose that <m>0\lt h\lt b-M</m>.
                Show that
                <me>
                  \frac{f(M+h)-f(M)}h\le 0
                </me>.
                How do we know that <m>L^+:={\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0^+}}\frac{f(M+h)-f(M)}h</m> exists?
                What can you conclude about <m>L^+</m>?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Repeat part (d) for <m>L^-:={\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0^-}}\frac{f(M+h)-f(M)}h</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Conclude that <m>L^+=L^-=0</m>.
                Why have we completed the proof?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
